1 Intro

WarwickLove is an online community for Warwick Students. With more than 7,000 likes and followers, it is the place where people express their idea and confession (Love?) anonymously. In this project, we try to discover what the community of students from the University of Warwick is most interested in, excited, and worried about by analysing the posts from the Facebook page.

2 Data Import

  • Data is fetched and parsed into a data frame from the Facebook page called ‘WarwickFessions’ (@warwickloveee), using Python library [facebook-scraper].
files <- list.files(pattern = "*.csv", recursive = TRUE)
  • Creating a dataframe
# read files

3 Data Wrangling

# create a function for text cleaning
cleanse_text = function(c) {
  c = iconv(c)
  c = gsub("[[:punct:][:blank:]]+", " ", c)
  c = stringr::str_replace_all(c, "\r", "")
  c = stringr::str_replace_all(c, "\n", "")
  c = trimws(c)
  return(c)
}

# create a function extracting only numbers
numextract <- function(string){ 
  str_extract(string, "\\-*\\d+\\.*\\d*")
}

4.2 Correlation

  • Let’s first check correlation in our data.
# numeric

ggcorrplot::ggcorrplot(corr$r, outline.col = "white", lab = T, tl.cex = 10)

  • Overall, popularity is highly and positively related to the number of likes, haha, comments, and shares, respectively.
  • However, among different types of reactions, they are also related to each other, which might impact on prediction using a supervised machine learning such as a regression model or a decision tree.

# create a new function for date visualization
plotnight <- function(dataframe, cat_var, topN=10) {
    var_col <- enquo(cat_var) # envi variable
    
    dataframe %>% group_by(!!var_col) %>% 
      summarize(median_pop = median(popularity)) %>% 
      filter(median_pop>0) %>% top_n(topN, wt=median_pop) %>% 
      ungroup() %>%
    ggplot(aes_(x=var_col, y=~median_pop, fill=var_col)) +
    geom_bar(stat='identity',show.legend = F)+
    scale_y_continuous(labels=comma)+
    labs(x="", y="Average Popularity") +
    theme(legend.position="none") +
    theme_minimal()
}

5 NLP

  • In this section, we will find the most frequent word (unigram) or words (bigram) used across the posts to gain an idea what posts are about.

5.1 Lemmatization

  • Let’s do lemmatization and POS-taggaing by loading the model using UDpipe library.
langmodel_download <- udpipe::udpipe_download_model("english")
langmodel <- udpipe::udpipe_load_model(langmodel_download$file_model)
  • Let’s do annotation.
postagged <- udpipe_annotate(langmodel,
                             df_5$text2,
                             parallel.cores = 10, 
                             trace = 1000)
  • We can create a data frame and explore it.
# create a data frame of pos-tagged texts
postagged <- as.data.frame(postagged)
head(postagged)

# save the working file as .rds
saveRDS(postagged,file = "postagged.rds")
  • Let’s filter and detokenize the postagged terms.
# read data
postagged = readRDS("postagged.rds")

# filter only nouns, adj, and adv
lematized <- postagged %>% filter(upos %in% c("NOUN",
                                              "ADJ",
                                              "ADV")) %>% select(doc_id,lemma) %>% group_by(doc_id) %>% summarise(documents_pos_tagged = paste(lemma,collapse = " "))

# combine tables
df_6 <- df_5 %>% left_join(lematized) %>% select(-text2)
## Joining, by = "doc_id"
# save the working file as .rds
saveRDS(df_6,file = "df_6.rds")

# check NA values across columns
which(colSums(is.na(df_6)) > 0)
## documents_pos_tagged 
##                   20
# drop NULL values
df_6 = df_6 %>% drop_na()

# remove postag
remove(postagged)

5.2 Unigram

  • We have removed unnecessary words or words with similar roots e.g., interest vs interested, including selecting only nouns, adjectives, and adverbs since it’s more meaningful and could be used for sentiment analysis.
  • We will now tokenize a sentence into a single word (unigram),

5.2.1 Tokenization

  • Let’s do word tokenization using unigram and tidy text approach
  • More information here: https://www.tidytextmining.com/tidytext.html
# word tokenization
token_df_all <- df_6 %>% unnest_tokens(word,documents_pos_tagged)

# check the language and remove non-English words
token_df_all$lan <- cld3::detect_language(token_df_all$word)
token_df_all <- token_df_all %>% filter(lan=="en")
  • We next back up the file.
saveRDS(token_df_all,file = "token_df_all.rds")
  • Let’s inspect text length.
# read data
token_df_all = readRDS("token_df_all.rds")

# calculate the token length

5.5 Readability

  • After calculating the formality, we can also extract the readability (easiness).
# create an empty data frame
readability_all <- data.frame()

# calculate readability score
for(i in 1:nrow(df_7)){
  
  readability_h <- data.frame() 
  
  this_text <- iconv(df_7$text2[i])
  this_text <- cleanse_text(this_text)
  
  tryCatch(readability_h <- flesch_kincaid(this_text),error=function(e){
    cat("Error parsing")
  })
  
  if(!is.null(readability_h$Readability)){
    
    readability_h <- readability_h$Readability
    readability_h$doc_id <- df_7$doc_id[i]
    readability_all <- bind_rows(readability_all,readability_h) 
  }
  
  print(i)
}
# join data tables
df_8 <- df_7 %>% 
  left_join(readability_all, by = "doc_id") %>% select(-c(all,word.count,sentence.count,syllable.count))

# back up the file
saveRDS(df_8, file = "df_8.rds")

5.6 Sentiment

batch_sentiment_by = function(reviews, batch_size = 200, ...) {
  review_batches = split(reviews, ceiling(seq_along(reviews)/batch_size))
  x = rbindlist(lapply(review_batches, sentiment_by, ...))
  x[, element_id := .I]
  x[]
}

sent_df = batch_sentiment_by(df_8$documents_pos_tagged) %>%

6 Modelling: Regression

6.1 Pre-processing data

  • Let’s partition the data by type of features.
# non-numerical data set
df_etc = df_10 %>% 
  select_if(negate(is.numeric)) %>% 
  select(image_group,weekday)

  select_if(is.numeric) %>% 
  select(comments:text_char,love:emoji_count,like_haha,

7 Analysis: Structural Topic Modelling

  • In this section, we are going to cluster the topics from all posts, which also helps identify which topics impact the most to the popularity.

7.2 Number of topics

  • Based on the work from [@Lee], we can set K=0 to initialize the algorithm that yield the possible maximum number of topics.
numtopics1 <- stm::searchK(result1$documents,
                           result1$vocab,K=0, 
                           prevalence = ~ popularity + comments + shares + love +
                             wow + care + sad + angry + like_haha + anger + joy +
                             trust + hour + image_group,
                           data=result1$meta,heldout.seed = 1) #36
  • For the numtopics1, the maximum number of topics is 36.

7.3 Model estimation

  • Once we have set the optimal K = 21, we will fit the model and see the relationship of topics to other features.
# fitting stm model using the number of topics (K) = 21 with threshold = 1%
suppressWarnings(library(stm))
finfit1 <- stm::stm(documents = result1$documents,
               vocab = result1$vocab,
               K = 21,
               prevalence = ~ popularity + comments + shares + love +
                             wow + care + sad + angry + like_haha + anger + joy +
                             trust + hour + image_group,
               #max.em.its = 75, 
               data = result1$meta,
               reportevery=10,
               gamma.prior = "L1",
               sigma.prior = 0.9,
               init.type = "Spectral",seed = 123)
